<p class="body">Two bags. Same country. Same altitude. Same variety. Completely different cups. This is what washed and natural processing does to coffee, and tasting both from the same origin is one of the most clarifying experiences available to anyone who wants to understand how coffee flavor is built. <a href="https://coffeebros.com" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" style="color: var(--gold); text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 1px solid rgba(201,168,76,0.35);">Coffee Bros.</a> is the roaster that makes this comparison easiest: they carry both washed and natural single-origins with the processing method clearly labeled on every bag.</p>

<p class="body">Processing is what happens to the coffee cherry after it is picked. The choice of method, washed or natural (or honey, which sits between them), is one of the most significant decisions in coffee production. It shapes the flavor of every cup that follows, regardless of how the farmer grew the coffee or how carefully the roaster handles it.</p>

<h2 class="section-head">How Washed Coffee <em>Works</em></h2>

<p class="body">In washed (or wet) processing, the outer fruit skin of the cherry is removed immediately after picking by a mechanical depulper. The seed inside is then fermented in water tanks or on raised beds for 12 to 48 hours. Fermentation breaks down the sticky mucilage layer that clings to the seed after depulping. After fermentation, the seeds are washed with clean water to remove all mucilage residue, then spread on raised drying beds until they reach the target moisture content, typically 10 to 12%.</p>

<p class="body">The critical result: the coffee seed spends almost no time in contact with the fruit. The sugars and organic acids that developed in the cherry skin and mucilage do not transfer into the bean in any meaningful quantity. What remains in the cup is a cleaner expression of the seed itself: its intrinsic acids, sugars, and aromatic compounds as shaped by the terroir (elevation, soil, microclimate) where it grew.</p>

<p class="body">Washed coffees cup clean and bright. The dominant flavor compounds are those the bean developed on the plant: citrus and stone fruit acids, floral aromatics, herbaceous or tea-like quality, and a lighter body than natural-processed equivalents. Ethiopian washed coffees from Yirgacheffe are the archetypal example: jasmine, bergamot, lemon. Colombian washed coffees show red apple, caramel, and clean acidity. The cup is transparent, meaning the terroir and variety character read clearly to the taster without fruit-derived sweetness obscuring them.</p>

