<h2 class="section-head">How Natural Coffee <em>Works</em></h2>

<p class="body">In natural (or dry) processing, the whole coffee cherry is dried with no fruit removal. Freshly picked cherries are spread in thin layers on raised beds or cement patios and left in the sun for two to six weeks, turned regularly to prevent mold and fermentation defects. During this time, the fruit around the seed slowly desiccates. As the cherry dries, the fruit sugars and organic acids migrate into the seed. When the cherry is dry enough to hull, the desiccated fruit is removed and the green coffee underneath carries with it a transformed flavor profile.</p>

<p class="body">The critical result: the coffee seed spent weeks surrounded by fermenting fruit. The sugars and fermentation byproducts have been absorbed into the bean's cellular structure. The cup of natural-processed coffee is heavier, sweeter, and more intensely fruit-forward. The origin's terroir is still present but it shares the cup with the fruit-derived flavors: blueberry, strawberry, dark cherry, wine, tropical fruit, and ferment-forward complexity that washed coffees do not produce.</p>

<p class="body">Natural coffees from Ethiopia, Colombia, and Brazil are the most common examples. An Ethiopian natural from Yirgacheffe or Guji cups with blueberry, strawberry, and wine notes that the same farm's washed coffee does not produce. A Brazilian natural cups with dark chocolate, dried fruit, and full body. The cup is heavier, sweeter, and less transparent to terroir than a washed coffee, because the fruit's contribution is as prominent as the bean's intrinsic character.</p>

