<h2 class="section-head">The Cup Comparison: <em>What to Expect from Each</em></h2>

<p class="body"><strong>Washed:</strong> Bright acidity, lighter body, clean and transparent, floral and citrus dominant, terroir-focused. Best for pour-over or drip brewing methods where clean cup clarity is the goal. Preferred by buyers who value precision and subtlety.</p>

<p class="body"><strong>Natural:</strong> Lower acidity, heavier body, sweeter, fruit-dominant, complex and layered. Best for French press, drip, or as an espresso base where sweetness and body are desirable. Preferred by buyers who want intense, fruit-driven cups.</p>

<p class="body"><strong>Honey:</strong> Between washed and natural depending on honey level (yellow, red, black). More body than washed, more clarity than natural. Good for buyers who want sweetness without the full intensity of a natural-processed coffee.</p>

<h2 class="section-head">Which to Try First</h2>

<p class="body">If you have never paid attention to coffee processing before, start with washed. A washed single-origin from Ethiopia or Colombia brewed as pour-over is the clearest possible window into what terroir and origin character mean in specialty coffee. It will likely taste lighter and more delicate than anything you have brewed before from a grocery store bag.</p>

<p class="body">Once you have a washed reference point, try a natural from the same origin or at least the same country. The contrast is startling the first time: the same region, transformed into a cup that tastes like blueberries or dark cherries. That comparison is one of the best education a coffee buyer can give themselves, and our full <a href="/learn/coffee-processing-methods">coffee processing methods guide</a> covers every method in depth if you want to continue from there.</p>

